<subSubSection pageId="102" pageNumber="103" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="102.[189,1399,527,661]" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">
This species used to be included in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kuhl" baseAuthorityYear="1817" box="[622,833,527,553]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Pipistrellus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kuhlii">
<emphasis box="[622,833,527,553]" italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Pipistrellus kuhlii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but as found by 
<bibRefCitation author="Gopfert" box="[1049,1347,527,554]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Gopfert" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" pagination="68 - 69" refId="ref262204" refString="Gopfert M. C., Heller K. G., Volleth M. &amp; Wasserthal L. T. 1995. Madagascar microchiropteran bats: new records including new species. Bat Research News 36 (4): 68 - 69." type="journal article" year="1995">
Göpfert 
<emphasis box="[1150,1211,527,553]" italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">et al.</emphasis>
(1995: 68)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Volleth" box="[189,486,563,589]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Volleth" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" pagination="25 - 46" refId="ref275486" refString="Volleth M., Bronner G., Gopfert M. C., Heller K. - G., von Helversen O. &amp; Yong H. - S. 2001. Karyotype comparison and phylogenetic relationships of Pipistrellus - like bats (Vespertilionidae; Chiroptera; Mammalia). Chromosome Research 9 (1): 25 - 46. https: // doi. org / 10.1023 / A: 1026787515840" type="journal article" year="2001">
Volleth 
<emphasis box="[284,346,563,589]" italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">et al.</emphasis>
(2001: 28)
</bibRefCitation>
, the sub-Saharan specimens have a different chromosome number than the specimens from Europe and northern Africa. For these sub-Saharan populations, 
<bibRefCitation author="Kock" box="[1147,1357,599,625]" firstAuthor="Kock" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" pagination="277 - 283" refId="ref268364" refString="Kock D. 2001. Identity of the African Vespertilio hesperida Temminck 1840 (Mammalia, Chiroptera, Vespertilionidae). Senckenbergiana Biologica 81 (1 / 2): 277 - 283." type="journal article" year="2001">Kock (2001: 277)</bibRefCitation>
reinstated the name 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[402,529,634,660]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Pipistrellus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hesperidus">
<emphasis box="[402,529,634,660]" italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">hesperidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="102.[189,1399,700,1084]" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">
Specimens belonging to this species were collected at three localities in the CRB area: two in 
<collectingCountry box="[1302,1398,700,726]" name="Rwanda" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Rwanda</collectingCountry>
(Mutura and Kitabi) and one in 
<collectingCountry box="[604,700,736,762]" name="Burundi" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Burundi</collectingCountry>
(Nyamugari Hill). 
<bibRefCitation author="Kearney" box="[948,1221,736,763]" firstAuthor="Kearney" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" pagination="629 - 631" refId="ref267427" refString="Kearney T. C. 2013 d. Pipistrellus hesperidus Dusk Pipistrelle. In: Happold M. &amp; Happold D. (eds) Mammals of Africa Volume IV. Hedgehogs, Shrews and Bats: 629 - 631. Bloomsbury Publishing, London." type="book chapter" year="2013" yearSuffix="d">Kearney (2013d: 630)</bibRefCitation>
indicates that 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[189,348,772,798]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Pipistrellus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hesperidus">
<emphasis box="[189,348,772,798]" italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">P. hesperidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed in a narrow band in eastern Africa, reaching from southwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[1311,1394,772,798]" name="Eritrea" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Eritrea</collectingCountry>
, over western 
<collectingCountry box="[348,450,807,833]" name="Ethiopia" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Ethiopia</collectingCountry>
, eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[554,704,807,833]" name="South Sudan" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">South Sudan</collectingCountry>
to northern 
<collectingCountry box="[850,944,807,833]" name="Uganda" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Uganda</collectingCountry>
, where it splits into two branches, one along the Kenyan-Tanzanian border reaching the coast, and a second along the great lakes to eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[189,314,879,905]" name="Zimbabwe" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Zimbabwe</collectingCountry>
and the eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[518,578,879,905]" name="South Africa" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">RSA</collectingCountry>
, reaching just north of Port Elizabeth. Additionally, she marked the presence of the species in the Mount 
<collectingCountry box="[653,775,915,941]" name="Cameroon" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
area and in 
<collectingCountry box="[935,1036,915,941]" name="Djibouti" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Djibouti</collectingCountry>
, with some further individual localities in northeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[486,585,950,976]" name="Somalia" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Somalia</collectingCountry>
, western 
<collectingCountry box="[696,789,950,976]" name="Zambia" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Zambia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[799,885,950,976]" name="Angola" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Angola</collectingCountry>
and southern 
<collectingCountry box="[1051,1112,951,977]" name="South Africa" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">RSA</collectingCountry>
. Furthermore, she refers to Jakob Fahr, who indicated that some records from West Africa might be misidentified. The SDM map confirms the presence of the species in eastern Africa. The records from West Africa might need to be re-examined.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
